Chapter One
Korolenko
It was 4:30 in the morning in Ithanian time. Korolenko hated waking up so early. Mainly because he had to be responsible for waking up the rest of his squad. He silently got out of bed, put on his combat gear, fastened his assault vest, and packed his belongings from the storage cabinet. He carefully picked up a small special box. He shouldered his rifle, hung his helmet on a small hook on his belt. The helmet was equipped with a full set of gear, including a breathing apparatus, goggles, and other necessary items. After checking his ammunition pouch, he quietly left the barracks, his boots making crunching noises on the muddy and icy ground.
He took out a lighter from his jacket pocket and a cigarette from another pocket. After lighting the cigarette, he took a gentle puff and then opened the door. In the past week, he had had to think hard just to wake up his subordinates. He no longer used a preset alarm clock, because half the time it didn't ring, and the speaker only emitted a faint hiss.
"Time to wake them up?" Korolenko turned around and saw Captain Nemets walking over.
“Yes.” Corin answered.
“What are you going to do this time?”
Corin hadn't had time to answer when the door opened, and Harris, Kress, and several others rushed out, already dressed and ready.
“Good morning,” Kress said.
“What woke you up?” Corin asked.
"First of all, we really don't want to see what method you're going to use to wake everyone up today. Second, the first squad to get up can have priority for breakfast," said a soldier named Raviq. "You know, how terrible those breakfasts are."
Korin said, "You're right, Corporal Raviq." He reached out and pressed the switch. An ear-piercing alarm immediately sounded in the barracks. He heard people shouting inside and a flurry of hurried footsteps.
"Good grief, Varturi," Nemychev said. "I thought they should have learned by now to get up with you."
"My recruits did manage to do that," Korin pointed to Harris, Cres, and Raviq. "But to be honest, their squad leaders and platoon commanders all knew to get up before the soldiers."
A few seconds later, the rest of the squad came out. They were all properly dressed and ready. Some of the new recruits looked sleepy, while others appeared very annoyed.
"Good morning, everyone," Kolen said cheerfully.
"Forgive me, sir, but why did you wake us up that way?" asked a突击队员 (Corporal).
"Because regular alarm clocks are just garbage. And Daybreak never sleeps in."
"Pack up your personal belongings," Kolen continued. As a lieutenant and deputy commander of the platoon, he had a duty to assist the platoon commander, Captain Borlatin Xiao, in supervising and leading the platoon. "We're not coming back. Sergeants and Lieutenants, you and your squads have 15 minutes for final checks and to bring along today's rations."
Members of Exodus Platoon quickly dispersed. They were part of the Second Assault Regiment of the Second Group Army. Before the merger, they were originally two independent platoons, Cohort and Dagger. This was an elite platoon, and Kolen felt complex emotions about being promoted to lieutenant, for many reasons.
Korran and First Squad Leader Nimich walked side by side along the brightly lit road of the base, with lights on both sides powered by generators. Most of the lights were red, helping them avoid enemy bombers. To counter them, Daybreak has begun using "Wild Weasel" tactics both in the air and on the ground.
"A new day, a new mission for the Hell's Vanguard," Nimich chuckled dryly. "Where are they going to send us this time?"
"Some frontline base outside of Yianlos. We're being sent to support the ground attack," Korran said, taking a drag of his cigarette. He somewhat blamed Kres for making him develop a smoking habit, but thinking back on the past year, they had endured countless battles, so he let it go and said nothing.
"That's terrible. The front lines are really tough right now," Nimich muttered. "All the messages we get here are 'support the war, assist the Kurkan front,' but why not support the Haulan front?"
"Well said, brother," Korran said, flicking the cigarette butt into the mud. "We'll be going with the First Armor Squad, no need to walk. Captain Xiao should be there."
"Captain Xiao let us ride with him?" Nimich asked in surprise.
"Yes. Honestly, he's not as bad as I imagined. I mean, he's not great, but he's not annoying either."
Kolun raised his thumb and index finger, pressing against the microphone on his throat, while moving his backpack onto his back. "Exodus, all units, assemble at the west vehicle yard after completing the mission. We will depart with the First Armor Platoon at 05:00."
Every few seconds, he received replies from his squad leaders. When they first arrived, Harris, Kress, and Ravik were lower-ranking non-commissioned officers. Since basic training on Earth, the four of them had been good friends. Kolun felt like he had known them for a long time, even though it had been less than two years. They were all squad leaders, but since a week ago, when the previous platoon leader was shot by a Daybreak sniper and had to retire due to injuries, Kress began leading the Second Platoon.
When they arrived at the vehicle yard, Kolun and Nimich's eyes fell upon about eight Kratos main battle tanks and four Stryker armored vehicles. Crew members were running around, ensuring their war machines were all functioning properly. Kolun quickly spotted Captain Boldin Xiao in the crowd, who was talking to the commander of the armor platoon. As they approached, Captain Xiao looked at them and came forward, his usual indifferent face showing no emotion.
"Ensign Nimitz... Lieutenant Varturi..." he said, Cole slowed his pace, Captain肖 looked at Cole's holster for the pistol, then looked up."Has the platoon been prepared yet?"
